\begin_layout Enumerate
Choose 3 from 26 with replacement hence 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$26^3=17576$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Choose 3 from 26 with replacement or (therefore the 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup$
\end_inset

) choose 2 from 26 with replacement hence 
\begin_inset Formula $26^{3}+26^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Choose 4 from 26 with replacement or (therefore the 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup$
\end_inset

) choose 3 from 26 with replacement or choose 2 from 26 with replacement
 hence 
\begin_inset Formula $26^{4}+26^{3}+26^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[1.18]
\end_layout

\end_inset

Imagine laying out the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 balls in a particular order then going through one by one and assigning
 a cell to each ball.
 This induces an implicit order on the cell assignments since the balls
 have a fixed ordering.
 The sample space is all such assignments, i.e.
 all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-tuples with each entry being an integer from 1 to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 There are 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$n^n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 different ways to assign the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 cells to the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 balls.
 A successful outcome is then one where exactly one cell is assigned twice,
 i.e.
 exactly two repetitions in the assignment list.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 ways to choose which cell will be assigned twice and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
binom{n}{2}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to choose which balls will bear the reptition.
 Then there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 ways to choose a cell that will remain empty.
 Finally there are 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-2)!$
\end_inset

 way to assign the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $n-2$
\end_inset

 cells to the 
\begin_inset Formula $n-2$
\end_inset

 balls.
 Hence the probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $n\binom{n}{2}(n-1)(n-2)!/n^{n}=\binom{n}{2}n!/n^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[1.21]
\end_layout

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

experiment
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $2r$
\end_inset

 shoes from 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 shoes without replacement.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{2n}{2r}$
\end_inset

 ways to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $2r$
\end_inset

 shoes from 
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 shoes, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 pairs of shoes.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{2r}$
\end_inset

 different ways to choose 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$2r$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 different pairs of shoes from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 pairs of shoes, i.e.
 since we'll only be choosing one shoe from each pair we must choose which
 pairs exactly it is we'll be taking a single shoe from.
 Then finally there are 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$2^{2r}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 different ways to choose either the left shoe or right shoe from each pair
 of previously 
\begin_inset Formula $2r$
\end_inset

 chosen shoes.
 Hence the fraction of choices of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$2r$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shoes from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$2n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shoes is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
[
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
text{number of choices of 2r pairs} 
\backslash
times 
\backslash
text{number of ways of choosing either left or right}}{
\backslash
text{number of ways of choosing 2r shoes}}=
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
binom{n}{2r}2^{2r}} {
\backslash
binom{2n}{2r}}
\backslash
]
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
