\begin_layout Plain Layout

[1.22]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

experiment
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is to draw 180 days from the year.
 The sample spaces is all 
\begin_inset Formula $180$
\end_inset

-element subsets of the 366 days, so there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{366}{180}$
\end_inset

 ways to draw 180 days from anywhere in the year for the 180 lottery tickets.
 In order that the days be evenly distributed there must be 
\begin_inset Formula $180/12=15$
\end_inset

 days chosen from each month.
 Then there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\underbrace{\binom{30}{15}\times\binom{31}{15}\times\cdots\times\binom{29}{15}}_{12}=\binom{30}{15}^{4}\times\binom{31}{15}^{7}\times\binom{29}{15}$
\end_inset

 ways to assign exactly 15 lottery tickets to each of the 12 months.
 Hence the probability of having all 180 lottery tickets evenly distributed
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\binom{30}{15}^{4}\times\binom{31}{15}^{7}\times\binom{29}{15}}{\binom{366}{180}}=.167\times10^{-8}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The experiment is again to draws days from the year.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{336}{30}$
\end_inset

 ways to choose 30 days from all the days in the year that are not in September
 
\begin_inset Formula $(366-30=336)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{366}{30}$
\end_inset

 ways to choose 30 days from any of the days of the year.
 Hence the probability of not selecting any days from September is 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\binom{336}{30}/\binom{366}{30}=0.0686905$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[1.23]
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

draw
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has 4 possibilities: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \text{HH},\text{HT},\text{TH},\text{TT}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 So there are 
\begin_inset Formula $4^{n}$
\end_inset

 different outcomes of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

draws
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Then there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{i}\binom{n}{i}$
\end_inset

 different each person could flip 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 heads, for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,1,2,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the probability of each person flipping the same number of heads
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=0}^{n}\binom{n}{i}^{2}/4^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To see that this equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{2n}{n}/4^{n}$
\end_inset

 we prove Vandermonde's identity, namely that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\binom{m+n}{r}=\sum_{k=0}^{r}\binom{m}{k}\binom{n}{r-k}
\]

\end_inset

To see that this is the case take 2 urns, one with 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 red balls and one with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 green balls and consider how many collections of size 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 can be drawn from both urns.
 Certainly it's 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{m+n}{r}$
\end_inset

.
 But it's also the sum, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, of the number of collections with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 red balls and 
\begin_inset Formula $n-k$
\end_inset

 green balls.
 For fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 this is 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{m}{k}\binom{n}{r-k}$
\end_inset

 and thence follows Vandermonde's identity.
 Finally letting 
\begin_inset Formula $m=r=n$
\end_inset

 and using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{n}{n-i}=\binom{n}{i}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{4^{n}}\sum_{i=0}^{n}\binom{n}{i}\binom{n}{i}=\frac{1}{4^{n}}\sum_{i=0}^{n}\binom{n}{i}\binom{n}{n-i}=\frac{1}{4^{n}}\binom{n+n}{n}=\frac{1}{4^{n}}\binom{2n}{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
