\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Number of flips until heads is geometrically distributed, i.e.
 the probability that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th flip is a head 
\begin_inset Formula $P(X=k)=(1-p)^{k-1}p$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 The probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 wins is tantamount to the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is odd (since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 flips first).
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\text{A wins})=P(X=k=2i-1|i=1,2,3,\cdots)=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}(1-p)^{(2i-1)-1}p=-\frac{(p-1)^{2}}{(1-p)^{2}(p-2)}
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1/2$
\end_inset

 this is 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{(1/2-1)^{2}}{(1-1/2)^{2}(1/2-2)}=\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Simplifying the result from (a) we get that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P(\text{A wins}) & =-\frac{(p-1)^{2}}{(1-p)^{2}(p-2)}\\
 & =-\frac{(1-p)^{2}}{(1-p)^{2}(p-2)}\\
 & =\frac{1}{2-p}\\
 & =\frac{p}{2p-p^{2}}\\
 & =\frac{p}{1-(1-2p+p^{2})}\\
 & =\frac{p}{1-(1-p)^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $P(\text{A wins})=\frac{1}{2-p}$
\end_inset

 we see that if 
\begin_inset Formula $0<p<1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}<P(\text{A wins})=\frac{1}{2-p}<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
